Creating a Basic Python Project Structure for ML Engineers</h1>
<h2 id="objective">Objective</h2>
<p>Learn how to create a well-organized Python project structure for
machine learning workflows, with separate directories for source code,
tests, and configuration.</p>
<h2 id="real-world-scenario">Real-World Scenario</h2>
<p>Imagine you are developing a simple machine learning pipeline for a
business use case. The pipeline should allow users to preprocess data
and train a basic model (e.g., linear regression). You want to organize
your code so that data processing, model logic, configuration settings,
and tests are separated into different directories and files. This
structure will help you collaborate with others, add new features (like
new models or preprocessing steps), and ensure your code works correctly
through automated tests.</p>
<p>By following this lab, you will create a project structure similar to
what professional ML engineers use, making your ML workflow scalable and
maintainable.</p>
<h2 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites</h2>
<ul>
<li>Python installed on your system</li>
<li>Basic understanding of command line operations</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>The Problem</strong>: The "Notebook Spaghetti" anti-pattern.
<strong>Standard Directory Structure</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>src/</code> or <code>&lt;package_name&gt;/</code>: Source code
(modules).</li>
<li><code>tests/</code>: Unit and integration tests.</li>
<li><code>data/</code>: Raw, processed, and external data (usually
excluded from Git via .gitignore).</li>
<li><code>notebooks/</code>: Exploration and scratchpad work.</li>
<li><code>conf/</code>: Configuration files (YAML, JSON).</li>
<li><code>models/</code>: Trained model artifacts.</li>
<li><code>docs/</code>: Documentation.</li>
</ul>
